{"id":"2212.04251","submitter":"Yang Huang","authors":"Yang Huang, Bing Sun, Zhoujian Cao","title":"Extending Gibbons-Werner method to bound orbits of massive particles","comments":"Some fundamental mistakes is found in this paper","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevD.107.104046","report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Gibbons-Werner method for the gravitational deflection angle of unbound\nparticles in static spherically symmetric spacetimes is based on Jacobi metric\nand Gauss-Bonnet theorem. When it is extended to bound massive particles, there\nexists two difficulties: (a) Bound orbits may overlap with themselves\nazimuthally. To extend the definition of deflection angle for unbound orbits to\nbound orbits, we divide the bound orbit into multiple segments such that each\nsegment does not overlap with itself azimuthally and can be regarded as an\nunbound orbit. (b) The infinite region constructed for unbound orbits in\nGibbons-Werner method is invalid for bound orbits, since the Jacobi metric of\nbound massive particles is singular at far region. To construct a suitable\nregion for bound orbits, we adopt the generalized Gibbons-Werner method\nproposed in our last work [Huang and Cao,\nhttps://journals.aps.org/prd/abstract/10.1103/PhysRevD.106.104043], so that the\nunphysical region in Jacobi space is avoided. What's more, taking the\nSchwarzschild spacetime as an example, we show the details of the calculation\nand obtain an analytical expression of the deflection angle between two\narbitrary points on the orbit.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 8 Dec 2022 13:08:12 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 9 Dec 2022 08:33:19 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 25 Apr 2023 04:15:06 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Wed, 7 Jun 2023 04:07:09 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-06-08"}
