{"id":"2304.01359","submitter":"Yaroslav Sergeyev","authors":"Yaroslav D. Sergeyev","title":"Some paradoxes of Infinity revisited","comments":"27 pages, 2 figures","journal-ref":"Mediterranean Journal of Mathematics (2022) 19, paper 143","doi":"10.1007/s00009-022-02063-w","report-no":null,"categories":"math.GM","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this article, some classical paradoxes of infinity such as Galileo's\nparadox, Hilbert's paradox of the Grand Hotel, Thomson's lamp paradox, and the\nrectangle paradox of Torricelli are considered. In addition, three paradoxes\nregarding divergent series and a new paradox dealing with multiplication of\nelements of an infinite set are also described. It is shown that the surprising\ncounting system of an Amazonian tribe, Pirah\\~{a}, working with only three\nnumerals (one, two, many) can help us to change our perception of these\nparadoxes. A recently introduced methodology allowing one to work with finite,\ninfinite, and infinitesimal numbers in a unique computational framework not\nonly theoretically but also numerically is briefly described. This methodology\nis actively used nowadays in numerous applications in pure and applied\nmathematics and computer science as well as in teaching. It is shown in the\narticle that this methodology also allows one to consider the paradoxes listed\nabove in a new constructive light.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 8 Dec 2022 10:30:51 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-04-05"}
